Date:12/14/2010 12:34:55 PM
From:B.K.Myers
It is not the auditor's job to detect fraud. That is a common misconception
held by many investors.

The financial statement audits done by external auditors are not designed to
detect fraud, plain and simple. Audits of financial statements really do two
things, when you break them down to the most basic objectives: (1) they double
check the math to see whether everything has been added and subtracted
correctly; and (2) they make sure that Generally Accepted Accounting Principles
(GAAP) have been correctly applied. That may not sound like much, but that is
what audits are. Audits were never designed to detect fraud.

http://www.expertfraud.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=13&Item
d=15

The Enron case was unique in that the base for the fraud was reported in their
financial statements - as a small footnote. The real error in that audit is
that it was a "material" amount and thus should have been more prominently
reported.

B.K.
